Internet 
exploration
• N = 84 undergraduate students with high 
and low levels of sustained attention (65 
females and 19 males, with a mean age 
of 20.46 years)
• Students were tasked with navigating 
the Internet for 20 minutes to learn 
about how tropical cyclones form

---PAGE---

• Students with high level of attention →more frequently guided their 
learning in a linear manner, alternating between search engine results 
and first links. Rarely did these learners select hyperlinks presented 
on the links themselves, and it was these students who performed 
better on the test
Internet 
exploration


---PAGE---

• Learners with low levels of sustained attention →typically took advantage 
of the opportunity to jump around between sources of information. While 
they alternated between search engine results and first links, the low-
attending learners engaged in far more exploration of the hyperlinks 
presented than the high-attending learners did. However, the hyperlinked 
sources were typically irrelevant. So, perhaps not surprisingly, those with 
short attention spans performed more poorly on the test than those who 
were able to focus longer
